The tachocline is the rotational shear layer uncovered by helioseismology immediately beneath the Sun’s convective envelope, providing a smooth match between the latitudinal differential rotation of the envelope, and the rigidly rotating radiative core (see, e.g., Spiegel and Zahn 1992; Brown et al. 1989; Tomczyk et al. 1995; Gough and McIntyre 1998; Charbonneau et al. 1999, and references therein). A number of magnetofluid instabilities can be excited within the tachocline, and the associated flow perturbations can develop a net helicity under the action of the Coriolis force. A systematic twist can then be imparted to an ambient mean toroidal field (or magnetic flux rope). This can drive an azimuthal mean electromotive force, and act as a T→P\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
