				\begin{document}$${\mathrm {Rm}}\lesssim 50$$\end{document}) the spatiotemporal evolution of the surface radial field is simply a diffused imprint of the equatorward drift of the deep-seated toroidal field. At higher circulation speeds, however, the surface magnetic field is swept instead towards the pole becoming strongly concentrated and amplified there for Rm exceeding a few hundreds.

From the modelling point-of-view, in the kinematic regime at least the inclusion of meridional circulation yields a much better fit to observed surface magnetic field evolution, as well as a robust setting of the cycle period. Whether it can provide an equally robust equatorward propagation of the deep toroidal field is less clear. The results presented here in the context of mean-field αΩ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
